docs.abstract: After years of expansion and billions in profits, Big Tech is pulling back from its famously lavish spending as a long boom finally ends.
docs.snippet: After years of expansion and billions in profits, Big Tech is pulling back from its famously lavish spending as a long boom finally ends.
docs.lead_paragraph: For much of last year, tech companies stumbled. Digital ad sales plunged. E-commerce sputtered. IPhone production stalled. And investors lost faith.

headline.main: Tech’s Biggest Companies Discover Austerity, to the Relief of Investors
headline.print_headline: Tech Embraces Austerity, To the Delight of Investors

byline.original: By Tripp Mickle, Karen Weise and Nico Grant

docs.abstract: With the exception of Apple, eight tech giants are no longer “pure growth” stocks, while Exxon and Chevron are, a new study says. Our columnist says: Buyer, beware.
docs.snippet: With the exception of Apple, eight tech giants are no longer “pure growth” stocks, while Exxon and Chevron are, a new study says. Our columnist says: Buyer, beware.
docs.lead_paragraph: It is impossible even to talk about the long bull market that ended in January 2022 without saying high-growth tech stocks propelled the market higher.

headline.main: Value Stocks? Growth Stocks? Markets Last Year Turned Everything Topsy-Turvy.
headline.print_headline: Value Stocks? Growth Stocks? It’s All Topsy-Turvy.

docs.abstract: The iPhone maker said sales of its flagship product were down 8 percent as it dealt with a factory shutdown and worries about rising inflation.
docs.snippet: The iPhone maker said sales of its flagship product were down 8 percent as it dealt with a factory shutdown and worries about rising inflation.
docs.lead_paragraph: When a Covid-19 outbreak in China forced a lockdown of Apple’s largest iPhone factory in November, the world’s most valuable company warned investors that it would lose sales. The question was: How much?

headline.main: Apple Revenue and Profit Down as iPhone Sales Slow

docs.abstract: Dispatchers for 911 are being inundated with false, automated distress calls from Apple devices owned by skiers who are very much alive.
docs.snippet: Dispatchers for 911 are being inundated with false, automated distress calls from Apple devices owned by skiers who are very much alive.
docs.lead_paragraph: FRISCO, Colo. — On a recent sunny Sunday morning, following a night of fluffy snowfall, tens of thousands of skiers flocked to the resorts of Summit County. Just minutes after the lift lines opened, sirens began blaring in the 911 emergency service center, where four staff members were taking calls and dispatching help.

headline.print_headline: 911 Gets a Call; It’s Your Watch, And It’s Worried

docs.abstract: Apple, Amazon and Alphabet all reported disappointing quarterly results, as they emphasized efforts to cut costs in the face of an economic slowdown.
docs.snippet: Apple, Amazon and Alphabet all reported disappointing quarterly results, as they emphasized efforts to cut costs in the face of an economic slowdown.
docs.lead_paragraph: Shares in tech companies are in retreat after investors got sobering news on Thursday about three of the industry’s giants — Alphabet, Amazon and Apple — including slowing demand for everything from iPhones to digital ads to cloud services.

headline.main: Tech Earnings Give a Wake-Up Call to Investors

byline.original: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Ravi Mattu, Bernhard Warner, Sarah Kessler, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

docs.abstract: Meta’s chief executive, Mark Zuckerberg, called 2023 the “year of efficiency,” a pronouncement that is reassuring investors and sparking a wider rally in tech stocks.
docs.snippet: Meta’s chief executive, Mark Zuckerberg, called 2023 the “year of efficiency,” a pronouncement that is reassuring investors and sparking a wider rally in tech stocks.
docs.lead_paragraph: Ahead of a mammoth day for tech earnings, investors already like what they see.

docs.abstract: Michael F. Bennet, a Colorado Democrat, cited national security, adding to bipartisan pressure on the Chinese-owned video app.
docs.snippet: Michael F. Bennet, a Colorado Democrat, cited national security, adding to bipartisan pressure on the Chinese-owned video app.
docs.lead_paragraph: Senator Michael Bennet, Democrat of Colorado, called on Apple and Google Thursday to remove TikTok from their app stores because of national security concerns, as bipartisan pressure on the Chinese-owned company escalates.

headline.main: Senator Calls on Apple and Google to Ban TikTok in App Stores
headline.print_headline: Senator Calls  For TikTok  To Be Banned In App Stores
